washington, february 11. – the senate went into executive session to-day, and on the doors being opened a message was received from the house announcing the passage of a resolution appropriating $300,000 for the relief of the sufferers by the floods. the senate passed the joint resolution and adjourned.

the quebec ice. quebec, april 27. the ice still remains jammed opposite the city, and the canal men have great difficulty in dragging their vessels over the hillocks of ice which in many places are piled up to the height of fifteen feet, and passengers have to pay, according to their appearance, from 50 cents to $2 each for crossing. the ferry company's steamers have gone into indian cove until the jam gives way. the steamers would soon cut it up, but they are afraid of breaking their screws, owing to the immense quantity of saw logs and other heavy timber embedded in the ice. in the meantime the people living along the river side are going for the logs in a lively way, a large number having been hauled up on the wharves and sawn up for firewood.

ald. grenier said they were being visited by a flood for the second time in twelve months, and he wanted to ask the chairman of the inundation committee what was being done to guard against their recurrence in future. he urged the practicability of the recommendations made by captain leger in regard to constructing a boom to stop the ice. ald. stevenson concurred in the recommendations of ald. grenier and in the importance of the subject. at the end of 1884 the inundation committee made a report which contained all the evidence taken on the subject of flooding, and they recommended that the evidence should be printed, but somehow the finance committee never did this. scientific men disagreed with the theory of capt. leger, who suggested that piers should be built across the river at lachine. they believed that the council or the government, or whoever did the work, might as well throw the money into the river as carry out the plan. ald. grenier - the government will not do it.

my suggestion is to leave the sewers alone, (they perform their office, except on abnormal occasions), and merely to protect them and those who use them from the action of these floods. a suggestion very similar to this was made to the council by the city surveyor in 1884, and with the council rests the blame of having taken no steps whatever towards remedying this well known devastating evil. it is compulsory on the part of property owners to connect with the public sewage; they have no alternative. it is the business of the civic authorities to see that their system of drainage is perfect, and by making the connection compulsory they take upon themselves the obligation of holding the property owners harmless against all damages from without, over which they can have no control . the remedy of the property owner is by an action at law for damages resulting from acts of negligence, in the same way as [end of image]

the scenes in the flooded districts were heartrending. many houses were under water above the second storey, and the unfortunate inmates, being unable to get out, were standing knee deep in the water. relief parties were organized, and with the aid of the boats and lumber managed to extricate the people and convey them to places of safety. quite a number of horses and cows were drowned in their stables, there being no time to rescue them. a large proportion of those summarily driven from their homes are laboring people. there will be great distress, particularly as it must be some time before the mills are in full running order again. steps are being taken to organize relief committees to attend to the most urgent cases. the river itself presents a magnificent sight. the ice is piled up in huge masses, some towering to a height of many feet and glittering like diamonds in the bright sunshine. at 12 noon the water receded, being a foot or more lower than its highest mark, but there is no certainty that another flood may not occur.

lady macdonald and daughter left this evening in company with miss mclymont and miss edith cox for the banff springs. it is understood that mr. h. casgrain, of the agricultural department, has been appointed chief clerk of dominion patent office, in the place of the late mr. a. j. camble. mr. casgrain has performed the duties of chief clerk for some months past. he is a brother of mr. p. a. casgrain, m.p., and of senator casgrain.

“we are pretty crowded,”		said a man from an upper window, “i have two families here besides my own, little to eat and no means of getting more for the present.  but we poor folks have got to help each other, and it might be my turn next,” he said with a resigning air.  “it’s a good thing for us the weather is warm.”  this was the general feeling, and not a grumble was heard anywhere save at the authorities whom the people seemed to hold responsible for the calamity.  considerable amusement was caused by the frantic endeavours of three girls to navigate a huge barge along the street.  when last seen they were hopelessly stranded on an ice reef, and half a dozen of the gallant griffintown gondoliers were hurrying to their assistance.  at the corner of ottawa and murray streets a dam had been formed by stranded icebergs, pieces of sidewalks and the other wreckage with which the street was littered.  over this the water rushed like a mill race and a rowboat which ventured too near was drawn into the vortex and swamped.  its occupants crawled out half drowned and managed to rescue their boat little the worse for wear.  a policeman who seemed to know as much about a boat as it did about him was seen rowing laboriously along and to all appearances making of point of running into everything that he could possibly come within reach of.  when he said was going to the station an incredulous smile crossed the faces of the spectator, but in such little veneration are the police held in this district that no one would go to his assistance.

the police on duty. the police of no.6 district were kept busy last night patrolling the streets in boats to prevent robberies, and succeeded in making half a dozen arrests for breaking windows.  the prisoners were taken either to the central or no. 8 station.  one man jumped out of the police boat at the corner of st. james and succeeded in making his escape.  two other men, arrested for a like offence, resisted violently, and the police were obliged to row to no.6 station for assistance.  just as the policeman at the door caught the rope the men made a final struggle for liberty, the boat upset and the occupants were thrown into the water.  the policemen climbed up the steps, while the prisoners crawled through the windows, only to find themselves in the basement of the station where the water was deeper than in the street.  they were fished out half drowned.

the growth of these colonies, more especially of the towns and cities, is very wonderful. victoria, though the smallest of the colonies, is foremost in arts and agriculture, and melbourne, her capital, among the youngest of her cities, is to-day the metropolitan city of the continent as regards population, and is still growing suburbanly at a marvellous rate. the latest published statistics give agricultural productions for the continent: wheat, 34,678,000 bushels, of this victoria produced 15,570,000; oats, 5,440,000 (victoria 4,717,000); barley, 1,490,000 (victoria produced of this number 1,070,000); potatoes, 245,000 tons (victoria produced 161,000); hay, all the colonies, 1,110,000 tons (victoria, 433,000 tons).

although the city of montreal has escaped the threatened danger of a flood, adjoining municipalities have not fared so well. this was especially so at longue pointe, where, owing to an ice jam on thursday night, the water rose so rapidly, that before the inhabitants were aware of the fact, the village was five feet under the water. the sidewalks, with the exception of a short, narrow strip, in the vicinity of the tollgate, have floated away. on hollowbridge street considerable damage was done to the lower part of the houses, while a shed on the same street stood in 14 feet of water.

even in homes that have been cleaned and disinfected, mould and mildew can still be present and can “cause or aggravate” a number of health problems, the montérégie regional health-board fliers pointed out. those problems include coughs, congestion, runny nose, sneezing and noisy breathing; rhinitis, bronchitis and asthma; irritated eyes, throat and nose; skin problems; fever, headaches, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea. homeowners should use gloves when they clean up, and thoroughly ventilate parts of the house hit by flooding, the health board advises. wet rugs should be thrown out and upholstered furniture thoroughly dried out - and if the smell of mildew persists, those items, to, should be junked. objects that are kept should be disinfected with a solution of bleach and detergent, rinsed and dried out.

for a while, it seemed that winter would never hit - december's total snowfall of 18 centimetres was way below the average of 55 centimetres. but 65 centimetres fell in january, above the average of 48, and so far this month, we have had 50 centimetres, well above the 41-centimetre average. the last time the montreal area was hit by a snowfall where the storm total was more than 25 centimetres was over a three-day period between jan. 14 and jan. 16, 1999, when we had to deal with 39.6 centimetres of snow.

ground-level ozone and particulates have been implicated in a wide array of health effects. long-term studies in ontario using hospital records have linked bad smog days with increased admissions for asthma, emphysema, chronic lung disease and respiratory infections. researchers also recently discovered smog is capable of sensitizing the cells that cause an asthma attack, so asthmatics suffer more frequent - and more severe - breathing attacks during smog episodes.

despite worrying claims by various groups, steady progress is being made against some of the most toxic air pollutants. concentrations of airborne benzene, a carcinogen in gasoline and industrial processes and an ingredient in smog, have fallen by 49 percent in canada since 1989, a recent report from the environmental commission of canada, the u.s. and mexico shows. and while there have been more smog advisories in recent summers in ontario, for example, it was mostly due to changes in the scale that shows how much smog is acceptable.

across canada, smog alerts are becoming more common. officials warn they’ll soon be more common, as officials move toward a national and more standardized way of measuring air quality. but are the health risks being exaggerated? please see smog, page a4

a winter of high-priced imported produce and bargain-priced local root vegetables and cabbage is the forecast - the high prices are a result of consecutive weather upsets in two southern growing areas. first came the florida freeze, which cut into crops of strawberries, string beans, green peppers and cucumbers, and wiped out the state’s supply of iceberg lettuce, radicchio and tomatoes. then it started raining torrents in california, flooding fields of lettuce and strawberries and preventing harvesting of these foods, as well as broccoli, cauliflower and - in some regions - celery.
